WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:12.800
Writing code can improve your workflow. We, the people in this room, and our friends joining

00:00:12.800 --> 00:00:22.680
online, we know this. But writing code can also be tricky, frustrating, and time-consuming.

00:00:22.680 --> 00:00:28.719
We also know this. And in my experience, it can be difficult to convince yourself, or

00:00:28.719 --> 00:00:34.119
maybe a manager, that it is worth spending time up front to write code for tasks like

00:00:34.119 --> 00:00:41.639
data wrangling, especially if there's an existing process that's already good enough.

00:00:41.639 --> 00:00:46.639
So my goal today is to demonstrate that it is worth spending this time up front to write

00:00:46.639 --> 00:00:53.480
code, because in the long run, it will save time, reduce errors, and improve the workflow.

00:00:54.480 --> 00:00:58.720
I'm going to use some examples from my work, and maybe these will motivate you to go off

00:00:58.720 --> 00:01:04.480
and write some code, or maybe you can use these examples to help convince a sceptical

00:01:04.480 --> 00:01:09.360
manager to let you write that code.

00:01:09.360 --> 00:01:14.040
So hi, everyone. My name is Danielle Dempsey. I'm a research scientist at a small company

00:01:14.040 --> 00:01:22.559
called the Centre for Marine Applied Research, or CMAR for short, in Nova Scotia, Canada.

00:01:22.639 --> 00:01:27.800
CMAR coordinates this really great coastal monitoring program to measure ocean variables

00:01:27.800 --> 00:01:34.680
like temperature, dissolved oxygen, and salinity from all around the coast of the province.

00:01:34.680 --> 00:01:40.599
This data can be used by scientists to study coastal ecosystems, industry to inform their

00:01:40.599 --> 00:01:45.839
site selection, government to inform their policy and management decisions, and the list

00:01:45.839 --> 00:01:47.760
could go on.

00:01:47.760 --> 00:01:56.040
So this is really valuable data, but for several years, it was rarely used because it was just

00:01:56.040 --> 00:02:01.559
stored on somebody's desktop in a myriad of CSV and Excel files that were really difficult

00:02:01.559 --> 00:02:06.680
and time-consuming to compile into a useful format.

00:02:06.680 --> 00:02:09.479
So why was this so difficult?

00:02:09.479 --> 00:02:15.320
It has to do with how the data are collected using what we call sensor strings.

00:02:15.320 --> 00:02:20.639
So a sensor string consists of a rope that's anchored to the ocean floor and suspended

00:02:20.639 --> 00:02:23.800
just below the surface by a buoy.

00:02:23.800 --> 00:02:28.679
There are sensors attached to the rope at different depths through the water column,

00:02:28.679 --> 00:02:34.360
and these sensors are recording data every one minute to one hour.

00:02:34.360 --> 00:02:39.720
Each sensor string is deployed in one location for a couple of months, up to a year.

00:02:39.720 --> 00:02:43.800
So they're really collecting a lot of data.

00:02:43.800 --> 00:02:49.059
And we use three different types of sensors that each report the data back in a slightly

00:02:49.059 --> 00:02:53.399
different format, like you can see on the screen.

00:02:53.399 --> 00:02:58.139
And you can start to appreciate how working with this data can be challenging, especially

00:02:58.139 --> 00:03:03.600
because there can be seven or more sensors on each sensor string, and each of these data

00:03:03.600 --> 00:03:09.639
files can be tens of thousands of rows long.

00:03:09.639 --> 00:03:15.039
So part of the reason that I was hired about two years ago was to help compile all of this

00:03:15.039 --> 00:03:21.000
data into a nice, tidy format that we could post online for any interested stakeholder

00:03:21.000 --> 00:03:25.399
to download and use in their own analyses.

00:03:25.399 --> 00:03:31.360
So about three weeks after I started this new position, I had a video call with my manager

00:03:31.360 --> 00:03:38.160
so she could show me the existing process for how this data is compiled.

00:03:38.160 --> 00:03:44.279
And I can remember very vividly sitting in my home office on a beautiful Thursday afternoon

00:03:44.279 --> 00:03:46.720
while she showed me this process.

00:03:46.720 --> 00:03:51.240
And let me tell you, this involved copying.

00:03:51.240 --> 00:03:52.960
It involved pasting.

00:03:52.960 --> 00:03:56.440
It involved sorting the data by a specific column.

00:03:56.440 --> 00:04:02.919
And it even involved writing down the Excel row numbers to use later on in the process.

00:04:02.919 --> 00:04:05.880
It was truly horrible.

00:04:05.880 --> 00:04:10.559
And I thought to myself, I will never do that.

00:04:10.559 --> 00:04:15.600
I offered to write some code to help with this, but my manager was a little bit skeptical

00:04:15.600 --> 00:04:22.279
at first, particularly because at this point I wasn't very confident in my data wrangling

00:04:22.279 --> 00:04:25.519
or package development skills.

00:04:25.519 --> 00:04:31.839
But eventually she gave me the thumbs up and I wrote a package called strings to help automate

00:04:31.839 --> 00:04:34.799
a lot of this process.

00:04:34.799 --> 00:04:38.839
To be clear, the package is named after our sensor strings and has nothing to do with

00:04:38.839 --> 00:04:40.959
character strings.

00:04:40.959 --> 00:04:46.559
So this was maybe a bit of a naive name choice, but it's only caused one small moment of confusion

00:04:46.559 --> 00:04:50.239
so far, and that's another story.

00:04:50.239 --> 00:04:55.480
For now, I'll move on to my first point.

00:04:55.480 --> 00:04:58.399
Writing code will save you time.

00:04:58.399 --> 00:05:04.119
Yes, you'll have to spend some time up front to develop the code, and you may have some

00:05:04.440 --> 00:05:08.880
learning curves to surmount, particularly if you're new to R, new to coding, but it

00:05:08.880 --> 00:05:12.600
will be worth it.

00:05:12.600 --> 00:05:22.519
So I spent a few weeks developing the backbone of the strings package, and as I said, at

00:05:22.519 --> 00:05:28.200
this time I didn't have a lot of experience with data wrangling, package development,

00:05:28.200 --> 00:05:34.119
working with dates and times, or importing and exporting large data files.

00:05:34.119 --> 00:05:38.519
So I spent a pretty substantial amount of time looking into different packages to help

00:05:38.519 --> 00:05:41.600
with those challenges.

00:05:41.600 --> 00:05:44.720
And these are just some of the packages that I ended up working with.

00:05:44.720 --> 00:05:48.679
You'll recognize most of them from the tidyverse, although there are a couple from outside of

00:05:48.679 --> 00:05:51.119
that collection.

00:05:51.119 --> 00:05:55.839
And the point I want to make here is that even though I hadn't used most of these packages

00:05:55.839 --> 00:06:03.040
before working on strings, I now use almost all of them in almost all of my coding projects,

00:06:03.040 --> 00:06:06.640
and that's because of the time that I spent learning about them to work on the strings

00:06:06.640 --> 00:06:08.640
package.

00:06:08.640 --> 00:06:12.920
So this is just one small example of how the skills that you learn working on one coding

00:06:12.920 --> 00:06:17.920
project are often really transferable to other projects.

00:06:17.920 --> 00:06:23.320
And in my case, the time that I spent working on the strings package also saved us time

00:06:23.320 --> 00:06:27.799
for processing that coastal monitoring program data.

00:06:27.799 --> 00:06:34.440
We estimate that it would have taken two years of work hours to compile all of that data

00:06:34.440 --> 00:06:37.920
with the horrendous old copy and paste method.

00:06:37.920 --> 00:06:44.119
Instead, within a couple of months, I had developed the package, myself and our student

00:06:44.119 --> 00:06:50.559
at the time had compiled and formatted all of the data, posted it online, and generated

00:06:50.559 --> 00:06:55.880
summary reports through R Markdown.

00:06:55.880 --> 00:07:00.839
It's also now really easy to train new people to compile this data using templates that

00:07:00.839 --> 00:07:03.959
I wrote to go with the package.

00:07:03.959 --> 00:07:12.320
Our current intern has compiled 71 deployments so far on top of all of his other work in

00:07:12.320 --> 00:07:16.200
just the 11 weeks that he's been with us so far.

00:07:16.399 --> 00:07:21.799
Something that would have taken over nine months of dedicated work time with the old

00:07:21.799 --> 00:07:24.640
method.

00:07:24.640 --> 00:07:28.839
And on the screen is just a tiny, tiny snapshot of our data.

00:07:28.839 --> 00:07:35.320
So this is temperature data from six deployments, or about four years, from an area called Birchie

00:07:35.320 --> 00:07:37.200
Head.

00:07:37.200 --> 00:07:41.320
And here, the temperature was measured at seven different depths through the water column,

00:07:41.320 --> 00:07:43.600
which are shown by color.

00:07:43.600 --> 00:07:48.320
And if you're interested in this, or any other CMR data, feel free to find me later

00:07:48.320 --> 00:07:49.320
this afternoon.

00:07:49.320 --> 00:07:55.279
I'm always really happy to talk about it.

00:07:55.279 --> 00:08:00.920
Writing code to help with your data wrangling can also help find and reduce errors in your

00:08:00.920 --> 00:08:03.339
data set.

00:08:03.339 --> 00:08:10.079
This will give you and your clients more confidence in the data, and also make whatever analysis

00:08:10.160 --> 00:08:14.920
you plan on doing with that data more reliable.

00:08:14.920 --> 00:08:19.519
And in my experience, errors can kind of creep into the data at different points along the

00:08:19.519 --> 00:08:24.440
data pipeline, especially wherever humans are involved.

00:08:24.440 --> 00:08:31.040
And so I've learned to write code to anticipate and sometimes even fix those errors.

00:08:31.040 --> 00:08:33.840
I have two examples of that for you.

00:08:33.840 --> 00:08:39.520
For the first one, after we had finished compiling all that sensor string data, I decided to

00:08:39.520 --> 00:08:45.280
plot the latitude and longitude of each sensor string to get an idea of the spatial coverage

00:08:45.280 --> 00:08:47.559
of the data.

00:08:47.559 --> 00:08:53.460
So you can imagine my surprise when my map looks something like this.

00:08:53.460 --> 00:08:58.119
So most of the sensor strings are showing up clustered around Nova Scotia, which is

00:08:58.119 --> 00:09:00.299
what we would expect.

00:09:00.299 --> 00:09:06.239
But there's also some sensor strings showing up way over here in Kazakhstan, which is not

00:09:06.239 --> 00:09:10.840
close to Nova Scotia and not even anywhere near the ocean.

00:09:10.840 --> 00:09:13.119
So what's going on here?

00:09:13.119 --> 00:09:18.400
After a little bit of digging, I discovered that our contractors who actually deploy these

00:09:18.400 --> 00:09:26.239
sensor strings have to manually record the latitude and longitude of each location.

00:09:26.239 --> 00:09:31.359
And because Nova Scotia is in the western hemisphere, longitude is typically recorded

00:09:31.359 --> 00:09:33.900
as a negative value.

00:09:33.900 --> 00:09:38.739
But every so often, it accidentally gets entered as a positive value, which is what's causing

00:09:38.739 --> 00:09:44.140
some of these sensor strings to show up way over there in Central Asia.

00:09:44.140 --> 00:09:50.059
So now, when the package first reads in this coordinate data, I'll get a warning if any

00:09:50.059 --> 00:09:52.659
of those longitude values are positive.

00:09:52.659 --> 00:09:59.619
So we can go in and fix that mistake before compiling all the data.

00:09:59.619 --> 00:10:07.179
A kind of more insidious error that I've seen is data from the wrong sensor in a file

00:10:07.179 --> 00:10:10.659
of data that's ready to be compiled.

00:10:10.659 --> 00:10:15.140
And this just happens when someone has what I call a human moment and accidentally puts

00:10:15.140 --> 00:10:18.419
the wrong file in the folder.

00:10:18.419 --> 00:10:23.340
In this example, data from one of the sensors on the blue sensor string has been put in

00:10:23.340 --> 00:10:28.659
the folder with all of the data from sensors on the green sensor string.

00:10:28.700 --> 00:10:31.099
And this issue is really twofold.

00:10:31.099 --> 00:10:38.099
One, the data set for the blue sensor string will be incomplete, and two, we will get false

00:10:38.099 --> 00:10:43.099
information about the area where the green sensor string was deployed.

00:10:43.099 --> 00:10:47.659
So this is really a critical error to be able to find and fix.

00:10:47.659 --> 00:10:54.859
Luckily, the data files are automatically named with the serial number of the sensor.

00:10:54.859 --> 00:11:01.539
And we keep track of which sensors are associated with each sensor string in deployment logs.

00:11:01.539 --> 00:11:07.020
And so I've written code in the package that will give an error if there's any missing

00:11:07.020 --> 00:11:18.179
extra or different files in that folder based on what we would expect from the log.

00:11:18.179 --> 00:11:23.299
Writing code to help automate your data wrangling can also make your workflow more traceable

00:11:23.299 --> 00:11:28.460
and reproducible, especially when compared to something like copying and pasting.

00:11:28.460 --> 00:11:34.619
And you can explain this to your non-coding managers with a metaphor.

00:11:34.619 --> 00:11:39.260
So copying and pasting in Excel is kind of like making a salad from just whatever is

00:11:39.260 --> 00:11:41.780
left in your fridge.

00:11:41.780 --> 00:11:45.500
Most of the time, it will probably taste okay.

00:11:45.500 --> 00:11:50.099
But eventually you will get something that doesn't taste quite right.

00:11:50.340 --> 00:11:54.739
Because you have no record of what went into that salad, it's really hard to tell what

00:11:54.739 --> 00:11:58.260
exactly is making it taste funny.

00:11:58.260 --> 00:12:03.359
And it's also hard to avoid making the same mistake in the future.

00:12:03.359 --> 00:12:07.900
As my colleague said when I was trying this metaphor out on her, you can't take the dressing

00:12:07.900 --> 00:12:11.859
back out of the salad.

00:12:11.859 --> 00:12:17.700
In contrast, writing code is more like writing and following a recipe.

00:12:17.700 --> 00:12:22.919
You can follow it step by step to get a delicious salad every time.

00:12:22.919 --> 00:12:27.140
And as an added bonus, you can even give this recipe to a friend so they can make their

00:12:27.140 --> 00:12:34.700
own salad or help you make dinner.

00:12:34.700 --> 00:12:40.140
As a more concrete example, for another part of our coastal monitoring program, we had

00:12:40.140 --> 00:12:47.419
these 65 current datasets that had to be compiled from a kind of messy text format into a tidier

00:12:47.419 --> 00:12:51.739
CSV format that was easier to work with.

00:12:51.739 --> 00:12:54.780
So I offered to write some code to help with this.

00:12:54.780 --> 00:13:00.140
But my managers again decided to have a couple of people instead copy, paste, and format

00:13:00.140 --> 00:13:02.979
in Excel.

00:13:02.979 --> 00:13:07.700
This took hours and hours of several people's time.

00:13:07.700 --> 00:13:10.900
But eventually they finished.

00:13:10.900 --> 00:13:16.580
And then we discovered that there had been a small mistake in how these original text

00:13:16.580 --> 00:13:19.940
files were exported from the sensor software.

00:13:19.940 --> 00:13:25.099
So all of the data needed to be compiled again.

00:13:25.099 --> 00:13:30.179
So this time I was asked to write some code.

00:13:30.179 --> 00:13:35.979
And within a few weeks, I had written a package that automated most of this workflow.

00:13:35.979 --> 00:13:42.099
So now if we want to make any other changes to this process, we've actually made a couple,

00:13:42.099 --> 00:13:47.059
just need to go in, tweak the code, press a button, and all of this data will be compiled

00:13:47.059 --> 00:13:51.780
within just a few minutes.

00:13:51.780 --> 00:13:57.299
And so if you have a repetitive task that you've been thinking about automating, I encourage

00:13:57.299 --> 00:14:01.580
you to go home after the conference and start writing some code.

00:14:01.580 --> 00:14:04.380
You don't have to write a whole package in a day.

00:14:04.380 --> 00:14:08.940
You can start with a function or two and just see where it goes from there.

00:14:08.940 --> 00:14:15.500
And if you do get some pushback from a skeptical manager, remind them that writing code will

00:14:15.500 --> 00:14:19.460
save time, reduce errors, and improve the workflow.

00:14:19.460 --> 00:14:24.500
And if you do use those points and it works, please let me know, because it would make

00:14:24.500 --> 00:14:26.900
my day.

00:14:26.900 --> 00:14:33.380
And the last thing I'll say is that my previously skeptical manager is now totally on board

00:14:33.380 --> 00:14:36.380
and really supportive of all my coding.

00:14:36.380 --> 00:14:41.780
She even showed me this super R, because she says that I've convinced her that R can do

00:14:41.780 --> 00:14:44.460
anything that we put our minds to.

00:14:44.460 --> 00:14:46.219
So thank you, and happy coding.

